<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-sets-of-real-numbers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Sets of Real Numbers</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Let <m>A,B\subseteq\R</m> and <m>c\in\R</m>. We use the following set
      operations:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><m>A+B:=\{a+b : a\in A,\ b\in B\}</m></li>
      <li><m>AB:=\{ab : a\in A,\ b\in B\}</m></li>
      <li><m>cA:=\{c\}A=\{ca : a\in A\}</m></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      In particular, <m>-A=\{-a : a\in A\}=\{a : -a\in A\}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      For <m>a,b\in\R</m> with <m>a\lt b</m>, the bounded intervals are:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><m>(a,b):=\{x\in\R \colon a\lt x\lt b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>[a,b]:=\{x\in\R \colon a\le x\le b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>(a,b]:=\{x\in\R \colon a\lt x\le b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>[a,b):=\{x\in\R \colon a\le x\lt b\}</m></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The unbounded intervals are:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><m>(a,\infty):=\{x\in\R \colon a\lt x\}</m></li>
      <li><m>[a,\infty):=\{x\in\R \colon a\le x\}</m></li>
      <li><m>(-\infty,b):=\{x\in\R \colon x\lt b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>(-\infty,b]:=\{x\in\R \colon x\le b\}</m></li>
      <li><m>\R=(-\infty,\infty)</m></li>
    </ul>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-bounded-subsets">
    <title>Bounded Subsets of <m>\R</m></title>

    <p>
      Let <m>A\subseteq\R</m>. A real number <m>b</m> is an <term>upper
      bound</term><idx>upper bound</idx> of <m>A</m> if <m>b\ge a</m> for all
      <m>a\in A</m>. A real number <m>b</m> is a <term>lower
      bound</term><idx>lower bound</idx> of <m>A</m> if <m>b\le a</m> for all
      <m>a\in A</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The set <m>A</m> is <term>bounded
      above</term><idx><h>bounded</h><h>above</h></idx>
      if it has an upper bound, and <term>bounded
      below</term><idx><h>bounded</h><h>below</h></idx> if it has a lower
      bound. We say <m>A</m> is <term>bounded</term><idx>bounded</idx> if
      it is both bounded above and bounded below. For any <m>b \in\R</m>,
      <m>b</m> is an upper bound of <m>A</m> if and only if <m>-b</m> is a
      lower bound of <m>-A</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-bounded-subsets-examples">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The following examples illustrate boundedness:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Let <m>A=(0,1)</m>. Then <m>1</m> is an upper bound of <m>A</m> and
            <m>0</m> is a lower bound of <m>A</m>. Hence <m>A</m> is bounded.
          </li>
          <li>
            Let <m>A=[2,\infty)</m>. Then <m>2</m> is a lower bound of
            <m>A</m>, but <m>A</m> has no upper bound in <m>\R</m>. So <m>A</m>
            is bounded below but not bounded above.
          </li>
          <li>
            Let <m>A=\N</m>. Then <m>1</m> is a lower bound of <m>A</m>, but
            there is no upper bound of <m>A</m> in <m>\R</m>. Therefore
            <m>\N</m> is not bounded.
          </li>
          <li>
            Let <m>A=\emptyset</m>. Every real number is both an upper bound
            and a lower bound of <m>A</m>. Thus <m>\emptyset</m> is bounded.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-bounded-iff-abs-bound">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A set <m>A\subseteq\R</m> is bounded if and only if there exists
          <m>M\in\R</m> such that <m>|a|\le M</m> for all <m>a\in A</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>A</m> is bounded. Pick a lower bound <m>m</m> and an upper
          bound <m>u</m>. If <m>M:=\max\{-m,u\}</m>, then <m>-M\le a\le M</m>
          for all <m>a\in A</m>, so <m>|a|\le M</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Conversely, if <m>|a|\le M</m> for all <m>a\in A</m>, then
          <m>-M\le a\le M</m> for all <m>a\in A</m>. Hence <m>A</m> is bounded
          below by <m>-M</m> and bounded above by <m>M</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-intervals">
    <title>Intervals</title>

    <p> Intervals is a central class of subsets of <m>\R</m>. They will appear
    repeatedly in limits, continuity, and topology on the real line.  </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-interval">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A subset <m>I\subseteq\R</m> is an
          <term>interval</term><idx>interval</idx> if it is non-empty and,
          whenever <m>x,y\in I</m> with <m>x&lt;z&lt;y</m>, one has <m>z\in
          I</m>.
	</p> 
	<p>A <term>nondegenrate interval</term> is an interval with at
	least two points.</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-interval-cardinality-r">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every nondegenerate interval <m>I\subseteq\R</m> has cardinality
          <m>|\R|</m>.
        </p>
      </statement> 
      <proof>
        <p>
          Every such interval <m>I</m> contains an open interval
          <m>(a,b)</m> and is a subset of <m>\R</m>.  It is enough to
          show <m>|(a,b)|=|\R|</m>.  The map <m>x\mapsto (x-c)/r</m>
          with <m>c=(a+b)/2</m>, <m>r=(b-a)/2</m>, is a bijection
          <m>(a,b)\to(-1,1)</m>.  Also <m>t\mapsto\tan(\pi t/2)</m> is
          a bijection <m>(-1,1)\to\R</m>.  Hence <m>|(a,b)|=|\R|</m>,
          so <m>|I|=|\R|</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-intersection-intervals">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The intersection of two intervals is either empty or is an interval.
        </p>
      </statement> <proof>
	<p>
	  Suppose the intersection of two intervals <m>I</m> and <m>J</m>
	  has at least two points <m>x&lt;y</m>.  Since <m>I</m> and <m>J</m>
	  are intervals, every <m>z</m> with <m>x&lt;z&lt;y</m> belongs to
	  both, so <m>z\in I\cap J</m>.  Thus, <m>I\cap J</m> is an interval.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-union-overlapping-intervals">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The union of two overlapping intervals is an interval.
        </p>
      </statement> 

      <proof> <p> Let <m>I,J</m> two overlapping intervals and <m>a \in I
      \cap J</m> . Take <m>x&lt;y</m> in <m>I\cup J</m>. If both are in an
      interval, then <m>[x,y]</m> is either a subset of <m>I</m> or <m>J</m>
      and hence is a subset of <m>I \cup J</m>.  Otherwise, <m>x</m> and
      <m>y</m> belongs to different intervals. After relabeling, we can assume
      <m>x\in I\setminus J</m> and <m>y\in J\setminus I</m>. If <m>a&lt;x</m>,
      then <m>x\in[a,y]\subseteq J</m>, contradiction. If <m>y&lt;a</m>, then
      <m>y\in[x,a]\subseteq I</m>, contradiction. So <m>x\le a\le y</m>.
      Then <m>[x,a]\subseteq I</m> and <m>[a,y]\subseteq J</m>, hence
      <m>[x,y]\subseteq I\cup J</m>. Therefore <m>I\cup J</m> is an interval.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>

</section>
